{"id":"1812.02604","submitter":"Anatoly Svidzinsky","authors":"Anatoly Svidzinsky and Robert Hilborn","title":"Comment on \"Tests of general relativity with GW170817\"","comments":"3 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In a recent paper \"Tests of general relativity with GW170817\"\n(arXiv:1811.00364 [gr-qc]) the authors claimed overwhelming evidence in favor\nof tensor gravitational wave (GW) polarization over vector by analyzing GW\nsignals measured by the LIGO-Virgo network. Here we show that the measured\nLIGO-Livingston signal is substantially reduced at certain frequency intervals\nwhich can be attributed to noise filtering. We found that if these regions are\nexcluded from the analysis then data are consistent with vector GW polarization\nand not with tensor. We show that if the signal accumulation method is applied\nover the entire detector bandwidth, including the regions in which the signal\nis depleted by noise subtraction, the result underestimates the LIGO-Livingston\nsignal amplitude. That smaller amplitude then leads to an erroneous conclusion\nthat favors tensor polarization over vector polarization for the GW.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 25 Nov 2018 19:33:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-12-07"}
